node.accessibility_caption: Photo by FBI on July 27, 2021. May be an image of phone and text that says 'Phone'.

node.text:
As spectators watched the 1996 Summer Olympics, Eric Robert Rudolph planted a bomb in Centennial Olympic Park in Atlanta. The subsequent blast killed one woman and harmed more than 100 other people—and triggered a five-year manhunt for Rudolph.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Before the bomb detonated on July 27, 1996, Rudolph twice called 911 to warn about the bomb. The FBI’s July Artifact of the Month is a pay phone from the group of pay phones where Rudolph placed the calls.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The FBI placed Rudolph on the Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list on May 5, 1998. He stayed on the list until May 31, 2003, when a police officer arrested him in North Carolina.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Click the link in our bio to learn more about the case.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#artifactofthemonth #history #mostwanted #olympics #summerolympics

node.accessibility_caption: An FBI agent named Tai listens to instructors during New Operator Training School in San Juan, Puerto Rico.

node.text:
Sweating under the heat of a tropical sun, a tactical vest, and the scrutiny of her instructors, an FBI agent named Tai sprinted up a hillside in San Juan, Puerto Rico, on her first day of New Operator Training School, a 10-week program for FBI San Juan SWAT team selectees.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Tai, one of five new FBI San Juan selectees, is believed to be the first Black woman selected for an FBI SWAT team. As she trained, she wasn’t focused on the weight of the milestone—only on clearing rooms and hitting targets in synchronicity with her teammates.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
"I'm not the biggest person. I'm not as strong as some of these guys. But as long as you have perseverance, you push through it and keep going," Tai said.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#fbi #fbiagent #fbisanjuan #specialagent #swat #sanjuan #puertorico

Director Christopher Wray visited the Pulse Memorial yesterday to honor the 49 victims who lost their lives during a shooting at the Pulse Nightclub in 2016.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
At the memorial he met with FBI Tampa Assistant Special Agent in Charge Ron Hopper, who served as the on-scene commander during the shooting.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
They reflected on the shooting near a wall that lists the names of the victims.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

node.text:
Honoring a fallen agent.
 
Fallen Special Agent Laura Schwartzenberger was honored during a baseball game at Nationals Park in Washington on July 4. She was one of two special agents killed while serving a federal search warrant in a crimes against children investigation earlier this year.
 
During her memorial service, Director Christopher Wray said, "She led a life of sheer determination, dedication, and courage. Of someone who really loved her work and the people she worked with. And of a woman who loved her family even more."
 
#wallofhonor

node.text:
Earlier this week, FBI Director Christopher Wray—along with U.S. Army Lieutenant General Flem B. "Donnie" Walker, Senator Richard Shelby, and Senator Tommy Tuberville—attended a groundbreaking ceremony for an Innovation Center at the Redstone Arsenal in Huntsville, Alabama.

This state-of-the-art building will serve as the FBI’s technical hub and will bring together technology-focused divisions to train, conduct cyber threat intelligence analysis and data analytics, and target rapidly changing technological threats. https://go.usa.gov/x6Hxm

node.text:
In June 1942, two Nazi submarines—each carrying four men—landed on American shores. Both groups brought explosive materials with them. Their mission: Sabotage American wartime production.
 
After George Dasch, one of the men, decided to confess, law enforcement personnel arrested all eight saboteurs within two weeks of their arrival—preventing them from causing destruction.
 
The FBI's June Artifact of the Month is a desk used during the trial of the saboteurs. Click the link in our bio to learn what prompted Dasch to confess.
 
#americanhistory #artifactofthemonth #fbi #fbihistory #history #worldwar2

node.text:
Edward Lee Howard’s boss said he was a good worker. His neighbors said he was a devoted husband and father. To his colleagues, Howard was a typical 34-year-old parent—until he defected to the Soviet Union in the mid-1980s.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The FBI's May Artifact of the Month is a dummy that helped former CIA officer-turned-spy Howard flee the country.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Click the link in our bio to learn about Howard's work as a spy for the Soviet Union.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#artifactofthemonth #fbi #fbihistory #history #ushistory

node.text:
Freeze! The FBI's February Artifact of the Month is a set of business cards—one for Clarice Starling and one for Jack Crawford—from "The Silence of the Lambs," which celebrates its 30th anniversary this weekend.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Several FBI employees served as consultants to the cast and crew. They reviewed the movie’s script, prepped the cast, corrected details in scenes, and played extras in scenes filmed at the FBI Academy in Quantico, Virginia.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Jodie Foster, who played Starling, met with female agents to inform her character. She received firearms training and attended new agent trainee classes.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Starling and Crawford may be fictional characters, but the legacy they’ve left on the FBI is real.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The film inspired a generation of women to join the FBI. Click the link in our bio to learn about a special agent who decided to join the FBI after she saw the movie for the first time.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
